# Container Query Card Implementation

## Overview
The web.dev article demonstrates using CSS container queries to create intrinsic, responsive cards that adapt based on their container width rather than viewport size.

## Key HTML Structure
```html
<div class="container">
  <div class="card">
    <div class="visual"></div>
    <div>
      <div class="meta">
        <h1>Card Title Here</h1>
        <h2 class="time">Subtitle</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="desc">Descriptive text supporting the card concept</p>
      <button>Action button</button>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
```

## CSS Implementation

**Container Setup:**
```css
.container {
  container: inline-size;
  width: 100%;
  max-width: 750px;
}
```

**Base Styles:**
```css
.visual { aspect-ratio: 1 / 1; }
.desc { display: none; }
.card { text-align: center; padding: 0.5rem; }
```

## Responsive Breakpoints

**At 350px width:**
```css
@container (min-width: 350px) {
  .card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 40% 1fr;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 1rem;
    text-align: left;
  }
}
```

**At 500px width:**
```css
@container (min-width: 500px) {
  .desc { display: block; }
}
```

## Key Benefit
As noted, "if you have this exact same component in different parts of your UI, it's able to use its own logic to resize and best fit its container," providing superior control compared to viewport-only media queries.

